You can sleep in tomorrow.

5
00:02:15,677 --> 00:02:17,262
That's what
Saturdays are for.

6
00:02:24,937 --> 00:02:26,313
Up against the wall.

7
00:02:26,396 --> 00:02:28,941
Come, come, come.

8
00:02:29,107 --> 00:02:30,442
All right.

9
00:02:30,567 --> 00:02:32,653
Got it. Got it.
Look, look!

10
00:02:32,736 --> 00:02:34,112
All right, sit down.

11
00:02:34,196 --> 00:02:35,696
Your breakfast
is getting cold.

12
00:02:35,780 --> 00:02:37,114
It's cereal.

13
00:02:37,156 --> 00:02:38,616
It's supposed to be cold.

14
00:02:59,929 --> 00:03:02,098
Sweetheart, we're here.

15
00:03:02,723 --> 00:03:03,850
Okay.

16
00:03:16,362 --> 00:03:18,030
Here's your books.

17
00:03:18,114 --> 00:03:19,365
Go ahead.

18
00:04:03,783 --> 00:04:07,204
Yes, ma'am. If you hold just a
moment, I'll get a supervisor for you.

19
00:04:08,538 --> 00:04:10,081
Yes,
she's coming right now.

20
00:04:10,165 --> 00:04:11,708
Just a second,
she'll be with you.

21
00:04:11,791 --> 00:04:15,712
Just one second, please. You deal
with this one. I'm not going near it.

22
00:04:17,714 --> 00:04:19,674
Hello, this is the supervisor.
How can I help you?

23
00:04:21,051 --> 00:04:22,927
I can see you're
on a party line...

24
00:04:23,719 --> 00:04:27,097
Unfortunately, some people do
listen in on party lines. We...

25
00:04:27,181 --> 00:04:28,807
Well, what is he doing?

26
00:04:32,102 --> 00:04:33,103
Oh, my...

27
00:04:33,187 --> 00:04:34,522
Everything all right?

28
00:04:35,564 --> 00:04:39,151
Yes, sir, it's fine. A lady was
having trouble with the connection.

29
00:04:39,401 --> 00:04:40,945
Hey, sport.
Hey, Mom.

30
00:04:41,028 --> 00:04:42,404
How was school?

31
00:04:42,488 --> 00:04:43,739
Okay.
Yeah?

32
00:04:43,781 --> 00:04:45,741
We learned
about dinosaurs.

33
00:04:45,824 --> 00:04:48,118
And I got in a fight
with Billy Mankowski.

34
00:04:48,202 --> 00:04:49,245
What happened?

35
00:04:49,328 --> 00:04:50,454
He hit me.

36
00:04:50,538 --> 00:04:52,039
Did you hit him back?

37
00:04:52,122 --> 00:04:53,415
Good.

38
00:04:53,499 --> 00:04:54,750
Rule number one,
remember?

39
00:04:54,834 --> 00:04:57,545
Never start a fight,
always finish it.

40
00:04:58,212 --> 00:04:59,755
Why'd he hit you?

41
00:04:59,839 --> 00:05:01,131
Because I hit him.

42
00:05:01,966 --> 00:05:03,509
You hit him first?

43
00:05:04,009 --> 00:05:05,052
Why?

44
00:05:06,262 --> 00:05:09,682
He said my dad ran off
because he didn't like me.

45
00:05:09,765 --> 00:05:12,101
Honey, your father
never met you,

46
00:05:12,184 --> 00:05:14,103
so how could he
not like you?

47
00:05:14,186 --> 00:05:15,979
Then why did he leave?

48
00:05:17,564 --> 00:05:21,025
Well, because the day
you were born,

49
00:05:21,609 --> 00:05:23,486
something else
arrived in the mail.

50
00:05:23,903 --> 00:05:25,488
And it was in a box a
little bit bigger than you.

51
00:05:25,572 --> 00:05:27,198
You know what was in it?

52
00:05:27,282 --> 00:05:29,033
Something called
responsibility.

53
00:05:29,576 --> 00:05:31,077
And to some people,

54
00:05:31,161 --> 00:05:33,955
responsibility is the
scariest thing in the world.

55
00:05:35,206 --> 00:05:39,377
So, he ran away because he was
scared of what was in that box?

56
00:05:39,460 --> 00:05:40,461
Uh-huh.

57
00:05:40,545 --> 00:05:41,880
That's just dumb.

58
00:05:41,963 --> 00:05:43,715
That is exactly
what I thought.

59
00:05:55,476 --> 00:05:57,854
<i>Did I miss Amos 'N Andy?</i>

60
00:05:57,937 --> 00:05:59,814
I'm afraid so, sport.

61
00:06:00,356 --> 00:06:01,774
Come now, time for bed.

62
00:06:07,238 --> 00:06:09,489
Are we still going
to the movies tomorrow?

63
00:06:09,573 --> 00:06:12,826
Uh-huh. I hear there's a
new Charlie Chaplin picture

64
00:06:12,910 --> 00:06:15,704
<i>and a new serial called
The Mysterious Airman.</i>

65
00:06:15,996 --> 00:06:17,164
Who's that?

66
00:06:17,247 --> 00:06:19,208
I don't know.
Nobody does.

67
00:06:19,291 --> 00:06:21,460
That's what makes him
so mysterious.

68
00:06:21,502 --> 00:06:22,503
Oh.

69
00:06:22,878 --> 00:06:25,005
Am I too heavy
for you to carry?

70
00:06:25,088 --> 00:06:27,758
Oh, no,
not for years.

71
00:06:27,841 --> 00:06:29,301
Not for years.

72
00:06:37,768 --> 00:06:39,353
<i>Hello?
This is Margaret.</i>

73
00:06:39,436 --> 00:06:40,604
Hi, Margaret.

74
00:06:40,687 --> 00:06:41,647
<i>So, how are you?</i>

75
00:06:41,730 --> 00:06:42,981
Fine.

76
00:06:43,023 --> 00:06:45,317
<i>Listen, Jean can't come in today
and now we're a little shorthanded.</i>

77
00:06:45,359 --> 00:06:46,610
When did she call in sick?

78
00:06:46,693 --> 00:06:47,736
<i>About half hour ago.</i>

79
00:06:47,819 --> 00:06:49,488
<i>I'm having a hard time
trying to find someone.</i>

80
00:06:49,530 --> 00:06:51,281
Well, what about Myrna?

81
00:06:51,365 --> 00:06:52,699
I know she could use
the extra hours and...

82
00:06:52,783 --> 00:06:54,868
<i>She's busy.
Can't you come?</i>

83
00:06:55,035 --> 00:06:57,704
No. No, no, no.
I just...

84
00:06:59,665 --> 00:07:03,417
I promised Walter that I'd take
him to the movies, is all, and...

85
00:07:03,501 --> 00:07:04,877
<i>Well, it's just until 4:00.</i>

86
00:07:04,961 --> 00:07:06,170
All right.

87
00:07:06,212 --> 00:07:08,047
Just...
Just until 4:00.

88
00:07:08,756 --> 00:07:10,091
I'll see you then.

89
00:07:16,264 --> 00:07:18,266
There's a sandwich
and milk in the fridge,

90
00:07:18,349 --> 00:07:19,851
and I've asked Mrs. Riley
and her daughter

91
00:07:19,934 --> 00:07:21,727
to stop in
in a couple of hours.

92
00:07:21,769 --> 00:07:23,938
I can take care of myself.

93
00:07:24,021 --> 00:07:26,649
I know you can. They're
checking on the house, not you.

94
00:07:34,907 --> 00:07:37,618
Tomorrow we will
go to the movies.

95
00:07:38,244 --> 00:07:42,665
And then we'll ride Big Red to Santa
Monica and take a walk on the pier.

96
00:07:42,748 --> 00:07:44,959
How does that sound?
Does that sound good?

97
00:07:48,588 --> 00:07:50,339
I'll be home
before it gets dark.

98
00:07:50,631 --> 00:07:52,300
I'm not afraid
of the dark.

99
00:07:52,383 --> 00:07:54,177
I'm not afraid
of anything.

100
00:07:55,051 --> 00:07:57,804
I know.
I know.

101
00:08:00,390 --> 00:08:01,933
Be good.

102
00:08:02,100 --> 00:08:03,685
I love you.

103
00:08:39,012 --> 00:08:41,473
We've got lines jammed
from here to Ohio.

104
00:08:41,556 --> 00:08:43,975
He says he needs to speak
to somebody in charge.

105
00:08:44,643 --> 00:08:47,729
I need your signature here
for a supply requisition.

106
00:08:47,812 --> 00:08:49,813
Number, please.
Number, please.

107
00:08:50,731 --> 00:08:52,149
Go ahead, please.

108
00:08:53,984 --> 00:08:56,237
All right, get me
the Omaha routing station.

109
00:08:56,320 --> 00:08:58,697
See if we can put our calls
through their switchers.

110
00:08:58,781 --> 00:09:00,366
Let's get this
console running, now.

111
00:09:04,662 --> 00:09:07,998
Christine. Good, I was
hoping to catch you.

112
00:09:08,415 --> 00:09:10,459
Look, I've been following
your work reports,

113
00:09:10,543 --> 00:09:12,753
and I just want to let you
know that I am very impressed.

114
00:09:12,837 --> 00:09:15,256
When I first suggested
hiring female supervisors,

115
00:09:15,339 --> 00:09:16,882
my superiors weren't
big on the idea.

116
00:09:16,966 --> 00:09:19,844
But you have held your own as well
as any of your male counterparts.

117
00:09:19,885 --> 00:09:20,928
Thank you, Mr. Harris.

118
00:09:21,011 --> 00:09:22,513
Oh, Ben, please.
Listen, I...

119
00:09:22,596 --> 00:09:23,681
Listen, the point is,

120
00:09:23,764 --> 00:09:26,559
we're looking to take on a manager
for our new Beverly Hills office.

121
00:09:26,642 --> 00:09:29,645
And if you're interested in the
job, I could write a report, or...

122
00:09:29,728 --> 00:09:31,522
That would be wonderful.
Thank you so much, sir.

123
00:09:31,605 --> 00:09:33,858
Okay, good,
so maybe we could...

124
00:09:33,941 --> 00:09:35,401
Could we speak about it
Monday? Yeah, absolutely.

125
00:09:35,484 --> 00:09:37,987
Would that be all right? Thank
you so much, sir. Thank you.

126
00:09:46,077 --> 00:09:47,370
Please!

127
00:09:49,998 --> 00:09:51,249
Please.

128
00:10:23,031 --> 00:10:24,365
Walter.

129
00:10:26,242 --> 00:10:27,452
Honey?

130
00:10:29,412 --> 00:10:30,788
Walter.

131
00:10:31,122 --> 00:10:32,373
Walter!

132
00:10:33,416 --> 00:10:34,751
Honey?

133
00:10:50,098 --> 00:10:51,308
Walter?

134
00:10:57,773 --> 00:10:58,941
Honey!

135
00:11:02,069 --> 00:11:03,403
Walter!

136
00:11:04,446 --> 00:11:07,032
Walter, it's time
to come in, honey.

137
00:11:10,285 --> 00:11:12,788
Suzie?
Have you seen Walter?

138
00:11:14,665 --> 00:11:15,749
No, Mrs. Collins.

139
00:11:15,833 --> 00:11:17,042
Sorry.

140
00:11:26,760 --> 00:11:27,845
Walter?

141
00:11:31,222 --> 00:11:32,598
Walter.

142
00:11:56,747 --> 00:11:57,999
<i>Number, please.</i>

143
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:00,084
May I please have
the police station?

144
00:12:00,168 --> 00:12:01,669
<i>I'll connect you.</i>

145
00:12:01,752 --> 00:12:02,753
<i>Lincoln Heights
Division.</i>

146
00:12:02,837 --> 00:12:04,630
Hello, my name is
Christine Collins.

147
00:12:04,672 --> 00:12:07,216
I live at 210
North Avenue, 23.

148
00:12:07,717 --> 00:12:10,178
And I'm calling
to report a missing child.

149
00:12:10,261 --> 00:12:11,721
Missing child.

150
00:12:11,804 --> 00:12:14,849
<i>What's your relation
to the child, ma'am?</i>

151
00:12:14,932 --> 00:12:16,350
It's my son.

152
00:12:16,475 --> 00:12:18,644
<i>How long has he been gone?</i>

153
00:12:19,020 --> 00:12:21,105
I'm not sure.
I just got home from work.

154
00:12:22,397 --> 00:12:24,608
It could be
since this morning

155
00:12:24,691 --> 00:12:26,401
or it could be
just the last hour.

156
00:12:26,485 --> 00:12:27,527
<i>Have you checked
around the neighborhood?</i>

157
00:12:27,611 --> 00:12:29,362
Yes, of course I did.

158
00:12:29,404 --> 00:12:31,490
<i>Well, maybe
he's lost track of time.</i>

159
00:12:31,531 --> 00:12:32,824
No. No, no.

160
00:12:32,866 --> 00:12:36,328
He always stays around the
house when it gets dark.

161
00:12:36,369 --> 00:12:38,455
Would you please send
someone down here?

162
00:12:38,538 --> 00:12:39,915
<i>I'm sorry,
but our policy is that</i>

163
00:12:39,998 --> 00:12:43,960
<i>we don't dispatch units on
missing child cases for 24 hours.</i>

164
00:12:45,212 --> 00:12:46,296
What?

165
00:12:46,379 --> 00:12:49,841
<i>Look, 99 times out of 100,
the kid shows up by morning.</i>

166
00:12:49,925 --> 00:12:53,803
<i>We don't have the resources to go chasing
every kid who runs off with his pals.</i>

167
00:12:53,887 --> 00:12:54,971
No, no, no.

168
00:12:55,055 --> 00:12:57,682
No, that's not Walter.
He doesn't do that.

169
00:12:57,724 --> 00:13:02,062
<i>With all due respect, ma'am, every
parent who calls says the same thing.</i>

170
00:13:03,104 --> 00:13:05,190
Please, please.

171
00:13:05,232 --> 00:13:06,900
<i>Look, there's
nothing I can do.</i>

172
00:13:06,983 --> 00:13:08,443
<i>I'll take your name
and your information,</i>

173
00:13:08,527 --> 00:13:11,154
<i>but that's all until the
morning, at the earliest.</i>

174
00:13:11,238 --> 00:13:14,241
<i>I'm sure he'll show up
by then. They always do.</i>

175
00:13:42,726 --> 00:13:44,436
Are you Mrs. Collins?

176
00:13:59,160 --> 00:14:03,706
<i>Our thoughts go out again
today to Mrs. Christine Collins</i>

177
00:14:03,789 --> 00:14:05,207
<i>of Lincoln Heights,</i>

178
00:14:05,291 --> 00:14:07,418
<i>whose young son,
Walter Collins,</i>

179
00:14:07,501 --> 00:14:10,044
<i>disappeared
nearly two weeks ago.</i>

180
00:14:11,129 --> 00:14:14,591
<i>Though she is not a
member of our congregation,</i>

181
00:14:14,799 --> 00:14:18,386
<i>we pray for her today
as we have every day,</i>

182
00:14:19,304 --> 00:14:21,681
<i>since we learned
of her plight.</i>

183
00:14:22,307 --> 00:14:24,642
<i>On the radio and
in the newspapers</i>

184
00:14:24,684 --> 00:14:27,645
<i>we are told that the Los
Angeles Police Department</i>

185
00:14:27,687 --> 00:14:32,275
<i>is doing its very best to
reunite mother and child,</i>

186
00:14:32,358 --> 00:14:34,777
<i>and I'm sure
that that is true.</i>

187
00:14:36,321 --> 00:14:40,950
<i>But given its status as
the most violent, corrupt</i>

188
00:14:40,992 --> 00:14:42,994
<i>and incompetent
police department</i>

189
00:14:43,036 --> 00:14:45,288
<i>this side
of the Rocky Mountains</i>

190
00:14:45,330 --> 00:14:48,791
<i>I am not sure
it's saying a great deal.</i>

191
00:14:56,508 --> 00:14:59,802
<i>Every day, new bodies
appear along Mulholland</i>

192
00:14:59,844 --> 00:15:01,887
<i>and in the ditches
of our cities,</i>

193
00:15:01,970 --> 00:15:08,352
<i>the work of Police Chief James
Davis and his aptly named Gun Squad.</i>

194
00:15:08,435 --> 00:15:11,814
<i>Every day, the needs
of honest citizens</i>

195
00:15:11,855 --> 00:15:16,109
<i>are put second to greed
and personal gain.</i>

196
00:15:16,693 --> 00:15:22,658
<i>Every day, this city sinks
deeper into a cesspool</i>

197
00:15:22,741 --> 00:15:27,538
<i>of fear, intimidation
and corruption.</i>

198
00:15:27,621 --> 00:15:30,040
<i>Once the City of Angels,</i>

199
00:15:30,082 --> 00:15:35,170
<i>Los Angeles has become
a place where our protectors</i>

200
00:15:35,212 --> 00:15:37,714
<i>have become
our brutalizers.</i>

201
00:15:38,090 --> 00:15:42,761
<i>Where to be the law is
to be above the law.</i>

202
00:16:30,600 --> 00:16:32,143
I understand.
Thank you.

203
00:16:32,226 --> 00:16:34,020
I will call back
in a few weeks.

204
00:16:34,520 --> 00:16:36,355
Thank you very much.

205
00:16:39,609 --> 00:16:41,944
Las Vegas Missing
Persons Department?

206
00:16:42,445 --> 00:16:44,238
Hello, this is
Christine Collins.

207
00:16:44,280 --> 00:16:47,158
I'm calling to see if you've
found any missing or lost children

208
00:16:47,241 --> 00:16:51,119
who meet the description
that matches Walter Collins.

209
00:16:53,079 --> 00:16:55,999
Oh, all right. Well,
please do. Please do call.

210
00:16:56,082 --> 00:16:57,626
And I'll call back
in a matter...

211
00:16:57,709 --> 00:17:00,462
In a week, if that's all
right. Thank you very much.

212
00:17:00,545 --> 00:17:01,546
Thank you.

213
00:17:17,229 --> 00:17:18,480
$2.

214
00:17:28,156 --> 00:17:30,450
Hell, I think I left
my wallet at home.

215
00:17:30,951 --> 00:17:32,410
Can I owe it to you?

216
00:17:33,245 --> 00:17:34,913
No credit.

217
00:17:34,996 --> 00:17:36,665
Pay up or I
call the cops.

218
00:17:36,706 --> 00:17:38,542
I'm sick of bums like you
coming around here.

219
00:17:38,625 --> 00:17:40,043
I'm not trying to
stiff you, chief.

220
00:17:40,126 --> 00:17:42,628
I just left my wallet
at home, that's all.

221
00:17:42,670 --> 00:17:45,673
I'll go back and get it.
Five, 10 minutes, tops.

222
00:17:48,968 --> 00:17:50,636
Got collateral?

223
00:17:51,053 --> 00:17:52,471
You can't ask for
better collateral

224
00:17:52,513 --> 00:17:54,849
than a man's own flesh
and blood, right?

225
00:17:55,850 --> 00:17:57,434
Now, you stay here, son.

226
00:17:57,685 --> 00:17:59,019
I'll be right back.

227
00:17:59,103 --> 00:18:01,647
But... Now, don't give me any trouble.

228
00:18:01,689 --> 00:18:03,691
He's a good man to
trust us like this.

229
00:18:04,525 --> 00:18:08,362
Now, you just stay here and
I'll go back and get my wallet.

230
00:18:11,615 --> 00:18:14,034
Ten minutes,
then I call the cops.

231
00:18:24,211 --> 00:18:25,713
Ah, hell.

232
00:18:30,759 --> 00:18:32,303
<i>Number, please.
Hello, Myrtle?</i>

233
00:18:32,386 --> 00:18:34,221
<i>Hello? Yeah, this is
Harve, down at the diner.</i>

234
00:18:34,305 --> 00:18:35,346
<i>Oh, hi, Harve.</i>

235
00:18:35,430 --> 00:18:36,598
Would you get me
Sheriff Larsen?

236
00:18:36,681 --> 00:18:37,557
<i>Sure thing.</i>

237
00:18:39,392 --> 00:18:41,102
You have
a nice day, too.

238
00:18:44,439 --> 00:18:46,608
Christine, I'm having trouble
with the connection here.

239
00:18:46,691 --> 00:18:48,568
I can't seem
to get through.

240
00:18:48,610 --> 00:18:51,029
I think so. Yeah, I think that's better.

241
00:18:54,407 --> 00:18:57,410
You have a person to
person call, Fairfax 2231.

242
00:18:57,452 --> 00:18:59,954
Long distance.
Sorry, can you repeat?

243
00:19:00,038 --> 00:19:01,789
I'll connect you
right away, ma'am.

244
00:19:01,956 --> 00:19:03,249
Thanks.

245
00:19:16,804 --> 00:19:18,139
Mrs. Collins?

246
00:19:18,515 --> 00:19:19,557
Yes.

247
00:19:20,433 --> 00:19:23,311
I'm Captain J.J. Jones,
Lincoln Park Juvenile Division.

248
00:19:24,270 --> 00:19:27,899
My office supervises all
runaway and missing child cases,

249
00:19:27,982 --> 00:19:29,858
including your son's,
and...

250
00:19:30,651 --> 00:19:32,528
He's alive,
Mrs. Collins.

251
00:19:36,448 --> 00:19:39,326
He was picked up two days ago by
local police in DeKalb, Illinois.

252
00:19:39,409 --> 00:19:40,828
He's safe and unhurt.

253
00:19:43,747 --> 00:19:46,333
He was in the company of some
drifter. We have an APB out for him,

254
00:19:46,416 --> 00:19:47,417
but he's safe.

255
00:19:48,544 --> 00:19:51,463
Thank you so much.

256
00:19:52,047 --> 00:19:53,715
Oh, Christine...

257
00:19:55,717 --> 00:19:57,010
That is so great.

258
00:20:04,977 --> 00:20:06,061
Thank you.

259
00:20:23,119 --> 00:20:24,704
There's
so much press.

260
00:20:25,371 --> 00:20:27,790
Yours is a story with a
happy ending, Mrs. Collins.

261
00:20:27,832 --> 00:20:30,042
People love happy endings.

262
00:20:30,793 --> 00:20:33,504
We better get a move on,
the train's pulling in.

263
00:20:35,047 --> 00:20:37,008
Back, boys. Back.

264
00:20:37,300 --> 00:20:39,135
Thanks.
Thanks, boys, thanks!

265
00:20:39,177 --> 00:20:40,678
I'll have a statement
for you in a few minutes,

266
00:20:40,761 --> 00:20:41,804
but the important
thing right now

267
00:20:41,888 --> 00:20:43,681
is to reunite this
little lady with her son,

268
00:20:43,723 --> 00:20:45,099
so if you'll excuse us.

269
00:20:48,686 --> 00:20:50,354
Stay right there.
Come on, don't rush.

270
00:20:51,272 --> 00:20:52,523
Easy, easy.

271
00:20:54,484 --> 00:20:56,986
Mrs. Collins, I'd like to
introduce you to James E. Davis,

272
00:20:57,069 --> 00:20:58,279
Chief of Police.

273
00:20:58,362 --> 00:20:59,322
Very nice to meet you.

274
00:20:59,405 --> 00:21:00,781
We don't get a lot
of positive attention

275
00:21:00,865 --> 00:21:02,325
from the boys in the
press these days,

276
00:21:02,408 --> 00:21:04,911
so it's good to be here with a
positive story, don't you think?

277
00:21:04,994 --> 00:21:06,037
Yes, sir.

278
00:21:06,120 --> 00:21:10,500
I take it you've been treated
well by my boys in the department?

279
00:21:10,541 --> 00:21:12,668
I couldn't file a report for 24 hours,

280
00:21:12,710 --> 00:21:14,003
and I thought that
maybe that was a...

281
00:21:14,045 --> 00:21:15,504
Technicalities aside.

282
00:21:17,547 --> 00:21:18,673
It was wonderful.

283
00:21:18,757 --> 00:21:19,883
Well, good.

284
00:21:21,927 --> 00:21:23,845
Then you won't have any trouble
telling that to the press,

285
00:21:23,887 --> 00:21:25,847
and the fact that the LAPD...

286
00:21:29,100 --> 00:21:30,185
Women.

287
00:21:30,268 --> 00:21:31,436
Hold on a second.

288
00:21:39,569 --> 00:21:41,112
Back, boys, back.

289
00:21:43,114 --> 00:21:44,366
Keep them back.

290
00:22:03,844 --> 00:22:06,847
Well, aren't you...
Aren't you gonna...

291
00:22:06,930 --> 00:22:08,181
That's not my son.

292
00:22:11,433 --> 00:22:12,601
What?

293
00:22:13,853 --> 00:22:15,187
What are you saying?

294
00:22:15,437 --> 00:22:17,273
It's not my son.

295
00:22:17,314 --> 00:22:19,692
Well, I'm sure
you're mistaken.

296
00:22:19,775 --> 00:22:20,860
I'm not mistaken.

297
00:22:20,943 --> 00:22:23,571
Well, he's been through
five terrible long months.

298
00:22:23,612 --> 00:22:25,739
He's lost weight,
he's changed.

299
00:22:25,823 --> 00:22:27,533
I would know my own son.

300
00:22:27,616 --> 00:22:30,411
All I'm saying is you're
in shock and he's changed.

301
00:22:32,246 --> 00:22:33,914
What's your name? Can
you tell me your name?

302
00:22:33,998 --> 00:22:35,624
Walter Collins.

303
00:22:37,877 --> 00:22:39,378
It's a common name.

304
00:22:39,461 --> 00:22:41,589
Where do you live, Walter?
You know your home address?

305
00:22:41,672 --> 00:22:44,925
I live at 210 Avenue 23,

306
00:22:45,259 --> 00:22:47,261
Los Angeles, California.

307
00:22:47,303 --> 00:22:49,221
And that's my mommy!

308
00:22:53,976 --> 00:22:57,354
Mrs. Collins, listen
to me. I understand.

309
00:22:57,438 --> 00:23:00,441
You're feeling a little uncertain
right now, and that's to be expected.

310
00:23:00,483 --> 00:23:02,859
A boy this age,
he changes so fast.

311
00:23:03,401 --> 00:23:05,862
We've compensated for that
in our investigation.

312
00:23:05,945 --> 00:23:08,907
And there's no question
that this is your son.

313
00:23:08,990 --> 00:23:10,992
That is not Walter.

314
00:23:13,203 --> 00:23:15,163
It's not Walter
as you remember him.

315
00:23:15,663 --> 00:23:19,876
And that's why it's important for
you to take him home on a trial basis.

316
00:23:21,336 --> 00:23:22,837
A trial basis?

317
00:23:22,921 --> 00:23:23,963
Yes, yes.

318
00:23:24,047 --> 00:23:27,592
Once he's around his
familiar surroundings,

319
00:23:27,675 --> 00:23:31,596
and you've given yourself time to recover
from the shock of his changed condition,

320
00:23:31,679 --> 00:23:34,432
you will see that
this is your Walter.

321
00:23:34,516 --> 00:23:37,060
Now, I promise you, I swear
to you, I give you my word.

322
00:23:37,143 --> 00:23:38,770
This is your son.

323
00:23:38,853 --> 00:23:42,398
Now, if you have any problems, any problems
at all, you come and you talk to me.

324
00:23:42,482 --> 00:23:43,817
I'll take care of it.

325
00:23:45,485 --> 00:23:47,821
I give you my word.
Trust me.

326
00:23:48,363 --> 00:23:51,866
Mrs. Collins, he has
nowhere else to go.

327
00:23:55,619 --> 00:23:56,870
Please.

328
00:24:01,458 --> 00:24:04,002
Maybe I'm not
thinking clearly.

329
00:24:04,044 --> 00:24:05,879
And...

330
00:24:07,339 --> 00:24:08,507
All right.

331
00:24:08,549 --> 00:24:11,093
All right, you're not
thinking clearly, that's right.

332
00:24:11,176 --> 00:24:12,594
Here we go!

333
00:24:13,095 --> 00:24:14,429
Thank you.
Thank you.

334
00:24:14,513 --> 00:24:16,557
Here, just turn
around here.

335
00:24:17,015 --> 00:24:18,725
How does it feel to have
your son home, Mrs. Collins?

336
00:24:18,767 --> 00:24:20,769
What'd you think when you
saw him for the first time?

337
00:24:20,853 --> 00:24:23,147
It's hard to explain.

338
00:24:23,230 --> 00:24:25,065
She was
shocked at first.

339
00:24:25,107 --> 00:24:28,068
She didn't recognize the boy,
which is perfectly natural.

340
00:24:28,152 --> 00:24:29,528
He's been through
quite an ordeal.

341
00:24:29,570 --> 00:24:31,071
How're you feeling, son?

342
00:24:31,113 --> 00:24:32,197
Bet it feels great
to be home.

343
00:24:32,239 --> 00:24:33,574
Yeah. It's great.

344
00:24:33,615 --> 00:24:35,784
The Los Angeles Police
Department is thankful

345
00:24:35,868 --> 00:24:39,079
for all the hard work done by the
DeKalb County Sheriff's Department

346
00:24:39,121 --> 00:24:41,748
in making this joyful
reunion possible.

347
00:24:41,832 --> 00:24:44,543
The LAPD is dedicated to
serving the public at all times.

348
00:24:44,585 --> 00:24:47,212
Can we get a photo with
mother and son, Captain?

349
00:24:47,296 --> 00:24:49,505
Absolutely! Here we are.

350
00:24:49,714 --> 00:24:51,340
Like that.
Like that.

351
00:24:51,424 --> 00:24:53,968
Squeeze together.
There you go, boys.

352
00:24:54,844 --> 00:24:56,596
This way, Walter.
Big smile.

353
00:24:57,096 --> 00:24:58,723
One more, please.
That's a good one.

354
00:24:59,891 --> 00:25:01,058
One more.

355
00:25:22,663 --> 00:25:24,081
The sandwich all right?

356
00:25:26,709 --> 00:25:28,085
Would you like
some more milk?

357
00:25:28,127 --> 00:25:29,253
No.

358
00:25:30,630 --> 00:25:31,923
No, thank you.

359
00:25:32,423 --> 00:25:33,633
No, thank you.

360
00:25:40,056 --> 00:25:44,100
You're covered in soot from the
train. You should take a bath.

361
00:25:55,320 --> 00:25:57,948
Pajamas are on the
edge of the bed.

362
00:26:00,992 --> 00:26:02,661
You okay?
You all right?

363
00:26:02,744 --> 00:26:04,704
I fell. Stupid tub!

364
00:26:05,455 --> 00:26:07,207
That's all right.

365
00:26:09,876 --> 00:26:11,670
You're circumcised.

366
00:26:17,134 --> 00:26:18,468
Get out.

367
00:26:19,803 --> 00:26:20,971
Move.

368
00:26:31,940 --> 00:26:33,984
Last time
I measured Walter,

369
00:26:34,067 --> 00:26:36,360
last time
I measured my son,

370
00:26:36,402 --> 00:26:38,487
he was inches taller
than you are now.

371
00:26:39,405 --> 00:26:40,865
Who are you?

372
00:26:42,032 --> 00:26:44,076
What are you doing here?

373
00:26:45,202 --> 00:26:46,704
Who are you?

374
00:26:47,997 --> 00:26:49,165
Who are you?

375
00:27:02,970 --> 00:27:03,846
He's not my son.

376
00:27:03,888 --> 00:27:04,972
Mrs. Collins...

377
00:27:05,055 --> 00:27:07,183
No, I don't know why
he's saying that he is,

378
00:27:07,224 --> 00:27:08,976
but he's not Walter
and there's been a mistake.

379
00:27:09,059 --> 00:27:11,061
I thought we agreed to
give him time to adjust.

380
00:27:11,145 --> 00:27:12,813
He's three inches shorter.

381
00:27:13,189 --> 00:27:14,523
I measured him
on the chart.

382
00:27:14,565 --> 00:27:15,983
Well, maybe your
measurements are off.

383
00:27:16,066 --> 00:27:18,986
Look, I'm sure there's a reasonable
explanation for all of this.

384
00:27:19,069 --> 00:27:20,404
He's circumcised.

385
00:27:21,030 --> 00:27:22,364
And Walter isn't.

386
00:27:23,657 --> 00:27:24,909
Mrs. Collins.

387
00:27:28,745 --> 00:27:30,580
Your son was missing
for five months.

388
00:27:30,622 --> 00:27:35,210
For at least part of that time in the
company of an as yet unidentified drifter.

389
00:27:35,251 --> 00:27:38,087
Who knows what such a disturbed
individual might have done?

390
00:27:38,880 --> 00:27:41,966
He could have had him
circumcised. He could have...

391
00:27:42,050 --> 00:27:43,510
Made him shorter?

392
00:27:48,431 --> 00:27:49,808
Why aren't you
listening to me?

393
00:27:49,891 --> 00:27:52,894
I am listening, damn it, I am listening.

394
00:27:52,936 --> 00:27:54,479
And I understand
your feelings.

395
00:27:54,562 --> 00:27:56,689
He's changed, no mistake, and that's...

396
00:27:56,773 --> 00:27:58,399
You've both been through
a terrible experience,

397
00:27:58,441 --> 00:28:01,361
and that's why he needs your
love and support to bounce back.

398
00:28:01,444 --> 00:28:02,946
He's not my son!

399
00:28:04,113 --> 00:28:06,241
Why are you doing this,
Mrs. Collins?

400
00:28:06,282 --> 00:28:07,408
Why are you doing this?

401
00:28:07,450 --> 00:28:10,537
You seem perfectly capable
of taking care of the boy.

402
00:28:10,620 --> 00:28:12,997
Your job pays you enough to
attend to his personal needs,

403
00:28:13,081 --> 00:28:14,791
so I don't understand
why you're running away

404
00:28:14,874 --> 00:28:16,668
from your responsibilities
as a mother.

405
00:28:16,751 --> 00:28:19,003
I am not running away
from anything!

406
00:28:19,087 --> 00:28:20,547
Least of all
my responsibilities!

407
00:28:20,630 --> 00:28:23,215
I am even taking care
of that boy right now,

408
00:28:23,298 --> 00:28:25,134
because I am all he has!

409
00:28:25,175 --> 00:28:27,469
What worries me is that you
have stopped looking for my son!

410
00:28:27,553 --> 00:28:32,057
Why should we be looking for
someone we've already found?

411
00:28:32,474 --> 00:28:35,561
Because you have
not found him.

412
00:28:35,644 --> 00:28:38,063
His identity
has been confirmed

413
00:28:38,147 --> 00:28:41,608
by the best minds in the
field of child identification,

414
00:28:42,067 --> 00:28:43,902
people who know
what they're doing.

415
00:28:43,986 --> 00:28:45,362
And I don't?

416
00:29:03,005 --> 00:29:05,841
I'm sorry.

417
00:29:06,800 --> 00:29:08,802
I appreciate everything that
this department has done

418
00:29:08,886 --> 00:29:11,013
and I know
how hard you're working.

419
00:29:11,096 --> 00:29:14,183
I really do, and I don't
want to cause any trouble.

420
00:29:14,266 --> 00:29:17,018
I just... There has
been a terrible mistake,

421
00:29:17,101 --> 00:29:19,270
and I need you to
help me correct it,

422
00:29:19,353 --> 00:29:24,192
so I can find my son
before it's too late.

423
00:29:26,444 --> 00:29:27,570
Please.

424
00:29:36,621 --> 00:29:40,291
I won't take up any more of
your time. I'm sorry I got upset.

425
00:29:40,374 --> 00:29:42,293
I'm sorry, very sorry.

426
00:29:54,972 --> 00:29:55,973
<i>Yes, Captain?</i>

427
00:29:56,057 --> 00:29:58,017
Sara, get Dr. Tarr
on the phone.

428
00:29:58,100 --> 00:29:59,227
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

429
00:30:04,565 --> 00:30:05,566
Mrs. Collins?
Yes?

430
00:30:05,650 --> 00:30:07,276
Dr. Earl W. Tarr.

431
00:30:07,360 --> 00:30:08,361
Captain Jones sent me.

432
00:30:08,443 --> 00:30:10,904
I consult with him from time
to time on juvenile cases.

433
00:30:10,946 --> 00:30:12,322
May I come in?

434
00:30:12,614 --> 00:30:14,574
Yes, thank you for coming.

435
00:30:14,616 --> 00:30:16,409
I was beginning to think
he didn't believe me.

436
00:30:16,493 --> 00:30:19,871
Well, I'm here now, and
we'll put all that to rights.

437
00:30:21,123 --> 00:30:22,707
Where's the boy?

438
00:30:25,460 --> 00:30:27,462
Ah! There he is.

439
00:30:28,797 --> 00:30:30,465
A handsome young man.

440
00:30:31,174 --> 00:30:33,009
He has your eyes,
doesn't he?

441
00:30:33,093 --> 00:30:35,303
And a little bit
of the nose.

442
00:30:35,595 --> 00:30:38,723
Very fit, in spite
of all his travails.

443
00:30:38,765 --> 00:30:42,102
A very resilient boy you've
got here, Mrs. Collins.

444
00:30:43,061 --> 00:30:44,729
I thought you were
here to help me.

445
00:30:44,771 --> 00:30:46,273
Well, I am.

446
00:30:46,356 --> 00:30:49,776
Captain Jones said that the boy had
been through some severe physical changes

447
00:30:49,860 --> 00:30:51,403
and asked me
to drop in on him

448
00:30:51,444 --> 00:30:54,072
to reassure you in your
time of motherly concern.

449
00:30:55,073 --> 00:30:59,536
My motherly concern is not for
him because he's not my son.

450
00:31:00,245 --> 00:31:04,748
Now, statements like that will
hardly help the boy's self-esteem,

451
00:31:04,832 --> 00:31:06,250
now will they?

452
00:31:07,501 --> 00:31:10,254
Captain Jones said something
about a change in height?

453
00:31:11,130 --> 00:31:12,173
Yes.

454
00:31:13,299 --> 00:31:14,633
Come.

455
00:31:16,760 --> 00:31:18,095
Against the wall.

456
00:31:21,974 --> 00:31:23,476
He's
three inches shorter.

457
00:31:24,268 --> 00:31:26,020
Ah, well...

458
00:31:26,979 --> 00:31:30,608
Hardly a mystery,
Mrs. Collins.

459
00:31:30,691 --> 00:31:34,987
We've known for some time that trauma
can affect the growth of children.

460
00:31:35,070 --> 00:31:37,239
Given the stress
of the past five months,

461
00:31:37,656 --> 00:31:39,783
his spine may have
actually shrunk.

462
00:31:39,825 --> 00:31:42,828
It's uncommon, but it's within
the realm of possibility.

463
00:31:45,498 --> 00:31:46,832
And circumcision?

464
00:31:50,503 --> 00:31:54,131
Very likely his abductor
thought it appropriate.

465
00:31:54,173 --> 00:31:56,966
After all, circumcision
is hygienically sound.

466
00:31:58,343 --> 00:32:01,346
Must have been quite
traumatic at the time.

467
00:32:02,680 --> 00:32:05,350
No wonder
he's submerged the memory.

468
00:32:07,811 --> 00:32:08,812
I...

469
00:32:08,895 --> 00:32:13,233
You see, there's a perfectly sound
medical explanation for all of this.

470
00:32:14,400 --> 00:32:16,694
But it's right for you
to raise the questions.

471
00:32:16,736 --> 00:32:19,781
You need to be apprised of all
changes the lad went through

472
00:32:19,864 --> 00:32:21,908
during his absence.

473
00:32:21,991 --> 00:32:25,245
Wouldn't I know whether
or not he's my son?

474
00:32:26,204 --> 00:32:27,705
I'm the mother.

475
00:32:28,248 --> 00:32:30,750
Which means you're in no
position to be objective.

476
00:32:31,626 --> 00:32:35,713
You are looking through the
prism of extreme emotion at a boy

477
00:32:36,089 --> 00:32:38,383
who has changed
from what you remember.

478
00:32:38,466 --> 00:32:40,510
He isn't the same boy
that left here.

479
00:32:40,552 --> 00:32:42,679
Just as a boy that goes
off to war and then returns

480
00:32:42,762 --> 00:32:44,597
is not the same anymore.

481
00:32:44,681 --> 00:32:49,351
And a mother's heart, driven
by intuition and emotion,

482
00:32:49,393 --> 00:32:51,854
sees these changes
and rebels,

483
00:32:52,563 --> 00:32:54,898
insists that
this isn't your son.

484
00:32:56,567 --> 00:32:58,277
Doesn't change the facts.

485
00:33:02,072 --> 00:33:06,368
I'm willing to put my theory to the
test of objectivity, Mrs. Collins.

486
00:33:07,202 --> 00:33:08,579
Are you?

487
00:33:15,836 --> 00:33:17,963
<i>It is
absolutely outrageous!</i>

488
00:33:18,046 --> 00:33:20,924
Calm yourself, calm yourself
and just listen to me.

489
00:33:21,008 --> 00:33:25,053
No, no, no.
No, you listen to me, please.

490
00:33:25,762 --> 00:33:29,600
This so called doctor paraded
me around my own neighborhood,

491
00:33:29,683 --> 00:33:33,020
like some kind of a derelict mother
who didn't even know her own son.

492
00:33:33,103 --> 00:33:35,063
<i>And what
was his findings?</i>

493
00:33:35,147 --> 00:33:37,441
He found what he
expected to find,

494
00:33:38,192 --> 00:33:41,111
what you obviously
told him he would find.

495
00:33:41,153 --> 00:33:42,612
<i>Mrs. Collins.
But that's not...</i>

496
00:33:42,695 --> 00:33:44,363
That's nothing
to be embarrassed about.

497
00:33:44,447 --> 00:33:48,910
That I was embarrassed
is not the issue.

498
00:33:51,078 --> 00:33:54,040
The point is that
you are wasting time

499
00:33:54,123 --> 00:33:57,251
when you should be
looking for my son.

500
00:33:57,335 --> 00:34:00,421
But the report is final,
Mrs. Collins.

501
00:34:01,380 --> 00:34:04,592
Well, then I want to receive
the report, so I can refute it,

502
00:34:04,634 --> 00:34:06,594
before it goes
to anyone else.

503
00:34:06,636 --> 00:34:07,887
Fine.

504
00:34:08,805 --> 00:34:11,057
Yes. Good day.

505
00:34:19,482 --> 00:34:21,818
I'm finished. Could I
go to my room now?

506
00:34:23,778 --> 00:34:24,946
Yes.

507
00:34:34,497 --> 00:34:36,123
Good night, Mommy.

508
00:34:37,582 --> 00:34:39,876
Stop saying that!

509
00:34:41,336 --> 00:34:43,421
Stop saying that!

510
00:34:43,672 --> 00:34:45,590
I'm not your mother!

511
00:34:48,635 --> 00:34:51,221
I want my son back.

512
00:34:51,304 --> 00:34:54,933
You're not him.
You're not my son!

513
00:34:57,894 --> 00:34:59,980
I want my son back.

514
00:35:00,897 --> 00:35:03,441
I want my son back!

515
00:35:03,984 --> 00:35:05,360
Damn you!

516
00:35:06,403 --> 00:35:08,864
I want my son back!

517
00:35:42,062 --> 00:35:44,315
I was wrong
to yell at you.

518
00:35:47,443 --> 00:35:49,028
You're just a child

519
00:35:50,571 --> 00:35:53,324
and I don't think you know
what you're doing,

520
00:35:53,407 --> 00:35:55,367
and the hurt
you're causing.

521
00:35:55,451 --> 00:36:00,915
But I need you to understand
that my son is my life.

522
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:05,169
He's all I have.

523
00:36:07,296 --> 00:36:11,509
And no matter what the police think,
and no matter what the world thinks,

524
00:36:13,093 --> 00:36:14,929
you and I,

525
00:36:16,013 --> 00:36:19,016
we both know the truth,
don't we?

526
00:36:19,308 --> 00:36:23,603
We both know that
you're not Walter.

527
00:36:23,645 --> 00:36:27,649
You just have to tell them
that you're not my son,

528
00:36:27,732 --> 00:36:29,692
so they can find my son.

529
00:36:33,279 --> 00:36:34,531
Please.

530
00:36:41,121 --> 00:36:43,998
We can talk tomorrow.

531
00:37:05,895 --> 00:37:06,980
Hello?

532
00:37:07,063 --> 00:37:09,107
<i>Is this
Mrs. Christine Collins?</i>

533
00:37:09,149 --> 00:37:10,733
Yes.

534
00:37:10,817 --> 00:37:12,402
My name is Gustav Briegleb.

535
00:37:12,485 --> 00:37:15,821
I'm the pastor over at
St. Paul's Presbyterian.

536
00:37:17,156 --> 00:37:19,158
Oh, yes, I've heard
your broadcasts.

537
00:37:19,199 --> 00:37:20,742
I'm...

538
00:37:20,826 --> 00:37:22,703
Thank you.

539
00:37:22,786 --> 00:37:25,330
<i>Have you read
the Times this morning?</i>

540
00:37:25,414 --> 00:37:26,540
No.

541
00:37:27,040 --> 00:37:31,253
<i>Well, maybe you should give it a gander
and then come over here to the parish</i>

542
00:37:31,336 --> 00:37:34,381
for breakfast, in, say, an
hour. I think we should meet.

543
00:37:37,050 --> 00:37:38,218
Hello?

544
00:37:46,185 --> 00:37:48,228
"Mysterious case of...

545
00:37:48,312 --> 00:37:50,689
"Acting on the request of the
Los Angeles Police Department,

546
00:37:50,731 --> 00:37:54,902
"Dr. Earl W. Tarr, child
specialist, examined Walter Collins

547
00:37:54,985 --> 00:37:56,779
"to determine the cause
of his loss of weight,

548
00:37:56,862 --> 00:37:59,490
"paleness, confusion,
and rundown condition

549
00:37:59,573 --> 00:38:00,783
"noticed since the
return of the boy

550
00:38:00,866 --> 00:38:03,327
"To his mother last Monday. "

551
00:38:04,912 --> 00:38:07,164
Lovely bit of phrasing,
isn't it?

552
00:38:07,206 --> 00:38:10,249
Noticed since the return
of the boy to his mother.

553
00:38:10,333 --> 00:38:13,085
Now, not only does that clearly
state you're the boy's mother,

554
00:38:13,169 --> 00:38:17,548
but one could infer from it that you're
somehow responsible for these changes.

555
00:38:17,590 --> 00:38:19,884
And that the police
department is concerned

556
00:38:19,967 --> 00:38:22,720
for the boy's welfare
while he's in your charge.

557
00:38:22,804 --> 00:38:25,306
You should try the eggs.
They're very nice.

558
00:38:25,973 --> 00:38:29,560
"'I examined the boy quite
thoroughly,' Dr. Tarr said,

559
00:38:29,644 --> 00:38:32,104
"'And it's clear that
he has something to tell.

560
00:38:32,188 --> 00:38:33,564
"'I'm sure that in time... "'

561
00:38:33,648 --> 00:38:37,777
...time he will give his boyish
story of the entire affair,

562
00:38:37,860 --> 00:38:40,655
but not until he has
faith in his listener.

563
00:38:40,738 --> 00:38:44,700
And that is what is lacking here,
faith in the poor lad's story.

564
00:38:45,493 --> 00:38:48,955
Course of my examination, I found
nothing to dispute the findings

565
00:38:49,038 --> 00:38:50,832
of the LAPD.

566
00:38:52,125 --> 00:38:54,252
Why would they do this?

567
00:38:54,335 --> 00:38:57,338
To avoid admitting
they made a mistake

568
00:38:57,421 --> 00:38:59,048
when they brought
back the wrong boy.

569
00:38:59,132 --> 00:39:01,801
Of course, anyone reading the
newspaper with half a brain

570
00:39:01,883 --> 00:39:03,927
would see
through it instantly.

571
00:39:04,010 --> 00:39:08,014
<i>Sadly, that would exclude about
half the readership of the Times.</i>

572
00:39:08,932 --> 00:39:13,103
Mrs. Collins, I have made it my mission
in life to bring to light all the things

573
00:39:13,186 --> 00:39:16,731
the LAPD wish none
of us ever knew about.

574
00:39:16,815 --> 00:39:22,863
A department ruled by violence, abuse,
murder, corruption and intimidation.

575
00:39:24,072 --> 00:39:27,409
When Chief Davis took over the
force two years ago, he said...

576
00:39:27,451 --> 00:39:30,829
We will hold court against gunmen
in the streets of Los Angeles.

577
00:39:30,912 --> 00:39:33,832
I want them brought
in dead, not alive,

578
00:39:33,915 --> 00:39:37,752
and I will reprimand any officer who
shows the least mercy to a criminal.

579
00:39:37,836 --> 00:39:41,298
He picked 50 of the most
violent cops on the force,

580
00:39:41,339 --> 00:39:44,926
gave them machine guns and permission
to shoot anyone who got in their way.

581
00:39:44,968 --> 00:39:47,471
He called them
the Gun Squad.

582
00:39:48,930 --> 00:39:52,851
<i>No lawyers, no trials, no questions,
no suspensions, no investigations.</i>

583
00:39:52,934 --> 00:39:54,811
Just piles of bodies.

584
00:39:55,644 --> 00:39:59,773
<i>Bodies in the morgues, bodies in the
hospitals, bodies by the side of the road.</i>

585
00:39:59,815 --> 00:40:04,236
And not because the LAPD
wanted to wipe out crime. No.

586
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:07,865
The LAPD wanted to
wipe out the competition.

587
00:40:07,948 --> 00:40:09,950
Mayor Cryer and half
the force are on the take.

588
00:40:10,034 --> 00:40:13,162
<i>Gambling, prostitution,
bootlegging, you name it.</i>

589
00:40:13,245 --> 00:40:16,499
<i>Because once you give people the
freedom to do whatever they want,</i>

590
00:40:16,582 --> 00:40:21,378
as the Lord found in the Garden
of Eden, they will do exactly that.

591
00:40:21,504 --> 00:40:25,299
This police department does not
tolerate dissent, or contradiction,

592
00:40:25,341 --> 00:40:27,760
or even embarrassment.

593
00:40:27,843 --> 00:40:32,598
And you are in a position to
embarrass them and they do not like it.

594
00:40:32,681 --> 00:40:35,518
They will do anything in
their power to discredit you.

595
00:40:35,601 --> 00:40:39,188
I've seen that happen too many
times to start going blind now.

596
00:40:39,271 --> 00:40:41,315
That's why I wanted
to meet you,

597
00:40:41,398 --> 00:40:44,235
to let you know what
you're getting yourself into

598
00:40:44,318 --> 00:40:47,780
and to help you fight it,
if you choose to.

599
00:40:47,863 --> 00:40:50,240
Reverend, I appreciate
everything that you're doing

600
00:40:50,323 --> 00:40:53,701
and everything
that you said,

601
00:40:54,619 --> 00:40:56,663
but I'm not on a mission.

602
00:40:56,746 --> 00:40:58,790
I just want my son home.

603
00:41:00,750 --> 00:41:03,044
Mrs. Collins, a lot
of mothers' sons

604
00:41:03,128 --> 00:41:06,297
have been sacrificed
to expediency around here.

605
00:41:06,381 --> 00:41:08,675
Your son, unfortunately,
would not be the first.

606
00:41:08,716 --> 00:41:12,095
But if you do it right,
he may very well be the last.

607
00:41:20,061 --> 00:41:22,397
He had two cavities
that needed filling.

608
00:41:22,480 --> 00:41:25,150
He put up a fight,
but I took care of it.

609
00:41:25,233 --> 00:41:26,484
And?

610
00:41:26,568 --> 00:41:30,196
Your son's upper front teeth were
separated by a small tissue, a diastema.

611
00:41:30,280 --> 00:41:32,782
It made them sit about
an eighth of an inch apart.

612
00:41:32,866 --> 00:41:35,285
The boy in that room
has no such gap.

613
00:41:35,368 --> 00:41:37,620
Can that change with age? Because
that's what they're gonna say.

614
00:41:37,704 --> 00:41:39,122
In some cases,
yes, it's possible.

615
00:41:39,205 --> 00:41:42,499
But the tissue between Walter's
teeth prevents that from happening.

616
00:41:42,583 --> 00:41:45,919
See, they can never come together
without an operation to sever the tissue,

617
00:41:46,003 --> 00:41:49,715
and I can tell you right now that
he has never had such an operation.

618
00:41:50,674 --> 00:41:53,135
Would you be willing to put
that officially in writing?

619
00:41:53,218 --> 00:41:55,971
Pardon my language,
but hell yes.

620
00:41:57,598 --> 00:42:00,893
Sounds like the
anesthetic's wearing off.

621
00:42:00,934 --> 00:42:04,313
On the other hand, maybe
I'll write that letter first.

622
00:42:04,396 --> 00:42:07,441
Give the little fella
something to think about.

623
00:42:17,534 --> 00:42:19,328
Well, if it is,
he's changed enormously.

624
00:42:19,411 --> 00:42:21,288
Do you know who I am?

625
00:42:21,371 --> 00:42:22,664
You're a teacher.

626
00:42:22,748 --> 00:42:25,918
Yes, but even teachers
have names. What's mine?

627
00:42:26,794 --> 00:42:28,629
I don't remember.

628
00:42:28,670 --> 00:42:31,507
I know you, but I don't
remember your name.

629
00:42:32,800 --> 00:42:35,135
Mrs. Fox.
Now, take your seat.

630
00:42:50,233 --> 00:42:54,237
I didn't say take a seat. I said
take your seat, the one assigned you.

631
00:42:54,320 --> 00:42:58,950
You must know where it is, you've
been sitting in it for over a year now.

632
00:43:07,166 --> 00:43:10,753
Mrs. Collins, if that's your
son, I'll eat my yardstick.

633
00:43:10,837 --> 00:43:14,215
Not only will I put it in writing, I
will testify to it in a court of law

634
00:43:14,298 --> 00:43:18,010
or to the President Calvin
Coolidge himself if I have to.

635
00:43:19,220 --> 00:43:20,304
Thank you.

636
00:43:23,141 --> 00:43:25,226
I'll see you tonight
for the broadcast.

637
00:43:25,309 --> 00:43:26,644
Good luck.

638
00:43:35,861 --> 00:43:37,112
Quick question, ma'am.

639
00:43:37,195 --> 00:43:38,363
Quick question!

640
00:43:38,447 --> 00:43:40,157
Mrs. Collins.

641
00:43:41,408 --> 00:43:43,493
Hello. My name is
Christine Collins.

642
00:43:43,577 --> 00:43:45,787
Good morning.
Good morning.

643
00:43:45,871 --> 00:43:50,417
On March 10th, my nine-year-old
son, Walter Collins, disappeared.

644
00:43:50,500 --> 00:43:52,210
And a five-month investigation

645
00:43:52,294 --> 00:43:56,256
led to a boy being brought to
Los Angeles from DeKalb, Illinois.

646
00:43:57,340 --> 00:44:00,719
They told me and all of you
that this boy was my son.

647
00:44:00,802 --> 00:44:02,637
He was not my son.

648
00:44:02,721 --> 00:44:04,639
The LAPD made a mistake,

649
00:44:04,723 --> 00:44:08,393
and that is the reason for
the supposed transformation.

650
00:44:09,019 --> 00:44:10,937
I have letters from his
teachers and his doctors

651
00:44:11,021 --> 00:44:13,398
all confirming that
he is not my son.

652
00:44:13,482 --> 00:44:17,611
I'm having them reprinted now, and
I'll have them for you tomorrow.

653
00:44:17,694 --> 00:44:21,156
I have given the LAPD every
opportunity to admit their mistake

654
00:44:21,239 --> 00:44:23,491
and renew the
search for my son.

655
00:44:23,574 --> 00:44:25,451
Since they have
refused to do so,

656
00:44:25,534 --> 00:44:28,412
it has forced me
to bring my case public.

657
00:44:28,496 --> 00:44:32,208
And I hope that this now will persuade
them to finish what they started

658
00:44:32,249 --> 00:44:34,919
and bring my son home to me.

659
00:44:35,002 --> 00:44:36,504
Thank you very much.

660
00:44:49,642 --> 00:44:50,893
Morelli!

661
00:44:51,477 --> 00:44:53,854
I want you to find the
Collins woman and get her here.

662
00:44:53,938 --> 00:44:56,148
And, Bill, bring her
in the back way.

663
00:44:56,232 --> 00:44:57,274
Yes, sir.

664
00:45:08,285 --> 00:45:09,787
This way, miss.

665
00:45:10,830 --> 00:45:11,914
Why are we going
in the back?

666
00:45:11,956 --> 00:45:14,750
Captain's orders. Front's
jammed with reporters.

667
00:45:19,671 --> 00:45:22,382
Please, sit down, miss. Captain
Jones'll be right with you.

668
00:45:22,465 --> 00:45:26,761
Hey! Anyone want to take a call
from the Canadian Mounties? Ybarra?

669
00:45:26,845 --> 00:45:28,096
What'd they do,
lose a moose?

670
00:45:28,179 --> 00:45:31,433
They need a juvenile living here
illegally deported back to Canada.

671
00:45:31,474 --> 00:45:34,894
He's living with his cousin on some
ranch near Riverside, in Wineville.

672
00:45:34,978 --> 00:45:36,020
You want it?
I'll take it.

673
00:45:36,104 --> 00:45:37,147
Got nothing better to do.

674
00:45:37,230 --> 00:45:38,648
You're a prince.

675
00:45:41,151 --> 00:45:42,569
Mrs. Collins.

676
00:45:42,652 --> 00:45:45,822
You can leave the boy.
She'll take care of him.

677
00:45:50,994 --> 00:45:52,245
Sit.

678
00:45:52,829 --> 00:45:55,707
Oh, you've caused us quite a
bit of trouble, Mrs. Collins.

679
00:45:55,790 --> 00:45:58,793
This situation has become an embarrassment
for the entire police department.

680
00:45:58,877 --> 00:46:00,420
It wasn't my intention
to embarrass anyone.

681
00:46:00,503 --> 00:46:01,963
Oh, no, of course not.

682
00:46:02,005 --> 00:46:05,717
You just told the papers we couldn't
tell one boy from another as a compliment

683
00:46:05,800 --> 00:46:07,969
for the months we spent
working on your case.

684
00:46:08,052 --> 00:46:10,429
You trying to make fools out of
us? Is that it? You enjoy this?

685
00:46:10,512 --> 00:46:12,639
Of course not.

686
00:46:12,681 --> 00:46:13,932
I want you to find my son.

687
00:46:14,016 --> 00:46:15,768
You know what your
problem is, Mrs. Collins?

688
00:46:15,851 --> 00:46:17,770
You're trying to shirk your
responsibilities as a mother.

689
00:46:17,853 --> 00:46:18,979
What?

690
00:46:19,062 --> 00:46:21,148
You enjoyed being a
free woman, didn't you?

691
00:46:21,190 --> 00:46:23,275
You enjoyed not having to
worry about a young son.

692
00:46:23,358 --> 00:46:25,861
You could go where you
wanted, do whatever you wanted,

693
00:46:25,944 --> 00:46:27,738
see anyone you wanted.

694
00:46:27,821 --> 00:46:30,324
But then we found your son,
and we brought him back.

695
00:46:30,365 --> 00:46:32,618
And now he's an
inconvenience to you.

696
00:46:32,701 --> 00:46:35,496
And that's why you
cooked up this scheme,

697
00:46:35,537 --> 00:46:38,373
to throw him to the state and get
the state to raise him for you.

698
00:46:38,457 --> 00:46:40,209
Isn't that true?
That is not true!

699
00:46:40,292 --> 00:46:42,628
No? Well, even the boy
says he's your son.

700
00:46:42,711 --> 00:46:44,004
Why would he say that?

701
00:46:44,046 --> 00:46:45,714
How would he know
to do that?

702
00:46:45,798 --> 00:46:47,758
I don't know.
I just know he's lying.

703
00:46:47,841 --> 00:46:50,219
Oh, maybe so.
Maybe he is a liar.

704
00:46:50,260 --> 00:46:52,554
But that's how he's
been trained, isn't it?

705
00:46:52,596 --> 00:46:54,473
Lying was born
in both of you.

706
00:46:54,556 --> 00:46:56,558
You're a liar and a
troublemaker and, if you ask me,

707
00:46:56,642 --> 00:46:58,644
you got no business walking
the streets of Los Angeles.

708
00:46:58,727 --> 00:46:59,770
Now wait a minute.

709
00:46:59,853 --> 00:47:01,730
Because either
you know you're lying,

710
00:47:01,772 --> 00:47:05,525
or you're not capable of knowing if
you're lying or telling the truth.

711
00:47:05,566 --> 00:47:07,110
So, which is it?

712
00:47:08,528 --> 00:47:11,072
You a derelict mother?
Or just plain nuts?

713
00:47:11,155 --> 00:47:13,366
'Cause from where I sit,
those are the only options.

714
00:47:13,407 --> 00:47:14,742
I'm not gonna sit
here and take this.

715
00:47:14,826 --> 00:47:17,078
You want experts? You want
doctors? I have a few of my own.

716
00:47:17,161 --> 00:47:18,371
Matron.

717
00:47:21,874 --> 00:47:26,254
Mrs. Collins, you still insist that
the boy out there is not your son?

718
00:47:26,295 --> 00:47:27,630
Yes, I do.

719
00:47:31,134 --> 00:47:32,426
Please, don't struggle.
What?

720
00:47:32,510 --> 00:47:33,678
No!
You'll only hurt yourself.

721
00:47:33,761 --> 00:47:35,012
What are you doing?
Hold still.

722
00:47:35,096 --> 00:47:36,639
You can't just do this.
No, you can't.

723
00:47:36,722 --> 00:47:37,849
You are to
convey the prisoner

724
00:47:37,932 --> 00:47:40,017
to the Los Angeles County General
Hospital Psychopathic Ward.

725
00:47:40,101 --> 00:47:41,227
What?

726
00:47:41,310 --> 00:47:43,521
You are to make
the following entry.

727
00:47:43,604 --> 00:47:46,190
Defendant states she's been
deceived by police and others,

728
00:47:46,274 --> 00:47:47,733
and that we have given
her a boy and tried

729
00:47:47,817 --> 00:47:50,611
to make her think it is her
son when she says it is not.

730
00:47:50,695 --> 00:47:53,781
Take her away.
No. No, no.

731
00:47:54,907 --> 00:47:56,116
Please. Please.

732
00:47:56,199 --> 00:47:57,367
Come on,
Mrs. Collins.

733
00:47:57,451 --> 00:47:59,327
No. No.

734
00:47:59,411 --> 00:48:00,579
This way.

735
00:48:04,875 --> 00:48:08,795
<i>Mrs. Collins has been known to
us since about March 10th, 1928</i>

736
00:48:08,879 --> 00:48:11,673
<i>when she reported her
nine-year-old son, Walter, missing.</i>

737
00:48:11,756 --> 00:48:14,426
<i>The boy was gone until
August 1928. Okay.</i>

738
00:48:14,801 --> 00:48:18,388
<i>Since his return, she has
complained that he is still missing</i>

739
00:48:18,472 --> 00:48:21,099
<i>and has made repeated
requests that he be found.</i>

740
00:48:21,183 --> 00:48:26,271
<i>She suffers from paranoia, delusions of
persecution and dislocation from reality.</i>

741
00:48:27,314 --> 00:48:29,858
<i>She may be a threat
to herself or others.</i>

742
00:48:29,983 --> 00:48:33,612
<i>We recommend that she be
conveyed to the psychopathic ward</i>

743
00:48:33,695 --> 00:48:35,405
<i>until her senses
